\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf4 Opinion Summary:  
\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf9 \tab The state licensed Sunshine Enterprises of Missouri, Inc., to operate as an unsecured, under-$500 lender in St. Ann. The city and its board of adjustment denied Sunshine a merchant's license, however, finding that the under-$500 lending is a service related to pawn shops and check cashing, which are prohibited under section 400.370 of the city's zoning ordinance. Sunshine appeals.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf9 \tab REVERSED AND REMANDED.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf9 \tab Court en banc holds:
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf9  This Court reviews the Board's decision, and the interpretation of an ordinance is a question of law. By authorizing uses with "similar" as well as the "same" characteristics of listed uses, subsection H of section 400.370 permits an unlisted use with characteristics that are not identical to those of a listed use. Under-$500 lending services, short-term consumer loans and under-$500 lenders are similar to permitted uses such as personal services and financial institutions, banks, savings and loan associations, and credit unions. Sunshine is not a pawnshop or a check-cashing business and, under section 400.370, it can operate in a general commercial district. Additionally, where a city ordinance prohibits a business that state law permits, the city must show the ordinance does not conflict with state law. State law authorizes under-$500 lenders, but the city has not shown that ordinance 2074, which prohibits short-term lending in all its zoning districts, is a valid exercise of its zoning power.
\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf4 Citation:  
\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf4 \par Opinion Author:  
\plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Duane Benton, Judge
\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf4 Opinion Vote:  
\plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf0 REVERSED AND REMANDED.  All concur.
\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf4 Opinion:
\par \pard \ltrpar\li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 \tab Sunshine Enterprises of Missouri, Inc. wants to operate a loan business in the city of St. Ann.  The city and its Board of Adjustment denied Sunshine a merchant's license, citing the city's zoning code.  The circuit court affirmed.  After opinion by the Court of Appeals, this Court granted transfer.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Mo. Const. art. V
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 ,
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  sec. 10.  
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Reversed and remanded.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qc \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf0 I.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The state licensed Sunshine to operate as an unsecured, under-$500 lender at 10015 St. Charles Rock Road, in St. Ann.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 408.500 RSMo 2000. 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0  That address is zoned "general commercial." 
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The city denied Sunshine a merchant's license, based on the zoning district of the address.  See 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 sec. 94.270 RSMo 2000
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 .  Sunshine appealed to the Board, for approval or a variance.  After the appeal was filed, but before the hearing, the city passed Ordinance 2074, amending the "definitions" in the zoning code.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The Board rejected Sunshine's appeal, relying on two zoning ordinances -- section 400.370 and Ordinance 2074.  Section 400.370 -- quoted in full in the appendix -- lists "PERMITTED USES" for a general commercial district:
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 A.\tab 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Retail sales . . .
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li720 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \tx1080 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 B.\tab 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Personal services, including barbershop, beauty parlor, cleaning and laundry pick-up establishments, photographers, shoe repair, tailoring and dressmaking, but excluding pawn shops and establishments whose primary business is check cashing and related services.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li720 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 C.\tab 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Household services . . .
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li720 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \tx1080 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 D.\tab 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Banks, savings and loan associations, credit unions, stock brokers and title companies.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 E.\tab 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Offices, including business, dental, general, laboratory, medical, radio and television and research.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li1080 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li1080 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 . . .
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li1080 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 H.\tab 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Uses having the same or similar characteristics as the foregoing uses.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \tx1080 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \tx1080 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The Board found that subsection B excludes Sunshine, because under-$500 lending is a service related to pawn shops and check cashing.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Ordinance 2074 states:
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li720 \fi0 \ri720 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 SHORT-TERM LOAN ESTABLISHMENT:  A business engaged in providing short-term loans to members of the public as a primary or substantial element of its operations and which is not licensed by the appropriate state or federal agency as a bank or savings and loan association.  Such business is prohibited in all zoning districts of the City of St. Ann.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl240 \sb0 \sa0 \par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The Board found that Ordinance 2074 also excludes Sunshine, because it offers "short-term loans."
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 \tab On certiorari, the circuit court affirmed the Board.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 89.110 RSMo 2000
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 .  Sunshine appeals.  This Court reviews the Board's decision -- not the circuit court's.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 State ex rel. Teefey v. Board of Zoning Adjustment
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 24 S.W.3d 681, 684 (Mo. banc 2000).
\par \pard \ltrpar\qc \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf0 II.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 According to the city, section 400.370 is a permissive use ordinance, so that only expressly listed uses are permitted.  See 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Frison v. City of Pagedale
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 897 S.W.2d 129, 133 (Mo. App. 1995).  The city claims that under-$500 lending is not expressly listed, and therefore not permitted.  The interpretation of an ordinance is a question of law for this Court.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Teefey
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 24 S.W.3d at 684.  This Court gives effect to the intent of the enacting legislative body, based on a review of the whole ordinance.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Id.
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 ; 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Wollard v. City of Kansas City
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 831 S.W.2d 200, 203 (Mo. banc 1992).
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 400.370 permits a wide range of commercial uses, including retail sales, personal services, household services, financial institutions, offices, and public buildings.  Subsection H, the catch-all, permits uses with "the same or similar characteristics" as a listed use.  By authorizing uses with "similar" as well as the "same" characteristics, subsection H permits an unlisted use with characteristics that are not identical to those of a listed use.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Under-$500 lending has the same or similar characteristics as personal services and financial institutions.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Sections 400.370.B, D, H.  
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Short-term consumer loans are similar to a personal service, as indicated by the exclusion of pawn shops and check cashing establishments.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 400.370.B.  
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Under-$500 lenders -- like banks, savings and loan associations, and credit unions -- offer unsecured loans to consumers.  See 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 secs. 362.105, 369.144(15), 369.229, 369.695.1, 370.070(2), 370.300, 370.310 RSMo 2000
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 ;
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  4 CSR 140-20.046 (2001)
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 .  Thus, under-$500 lending is a permitted use.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Sections 400.370.B, D, H.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 \tab The city contends that under-$500 lenders are expressly excluded as "pawn shops and establishments whose primary business is check cashing and related services."  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 400.370
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 .
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 B.
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0   The second phrase "establishments whose primary business is check cashing and related services" refers to one type of excluded business.  If "related services" were a separate business, the ordinance would read (addition bracketed; deletion stricken):  "pawn shops[,] 
\plain \strike \f1 \fs20 \cf0 and
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0  establishments whose primary business is check cashing and related services."
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf2 (FN1)
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0   
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 \tab Sunshine is not a "pawn shop."  Pawn shops are defined and licensed under a different state law.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Sections 367.011(4), 367.043.1 RSMo 2000.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Nor is Sunshine an "establishment whose primary business is check cashing and related services." 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 When Sunshine lends money, it accepts a check for the amount of the loan and fees, post-dated to the due date.  Fees increase with the amount of the loan.  At the due date, the customer can pay cash for the loan and fees, let Sunshine cash the check, or "buy" an extension.  If Sunshine cashes the check and it is not honored, Sunshine pursues remedies against the customer, the 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 drawer/payer
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0  of the check.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 According to the record, check-cashing businesses are not licensed by the state.  Check-cashing businesses charge customers a fee to cash a check, typically issued by a third party.  The fee increases with the likelihood of dishonor.  If the check is dishonored, the check-cashing business's recourse is primarily against the third party, the 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 drawer
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 /
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 payer
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0  of the check -- not the customer, who typically is the 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 payee
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 .
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Sunshine's use of a check does not make it a check-cashing business.  Sunshine's primary business is making loans, not cashing third-party checks and performing related services.  Sunshine is not an "establishment whose primary business is check cashing and related services."  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 400.370.B.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Under section 400.370, Sunshine can operate in a general commercial district, because subsections B, D, and H permit, and subsection B does not exclude, an under-$500 lender.  
\par \pard \ltrpar\qc \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf0 III.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The city claims that, even if permitted by section 400.370, Sunshine is excluded by Ordinance 2074.  The city views Ordinance 2074 as a land use "zoning" regulation.  See 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 secs. 89.010-040 RSMo 2000
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 .  Zoning ordinances are presumptively within the police power.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Flora Realty and Inv. Co. v. City of Ladue, 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 246 S.W.2d 771, 778 (Mo. banc 1952);
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  State ex rel. Helujon, Ltd. v. Jefferson County
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 964 S.W.2d 531, 536 (Mo. App. 1998).  This Court has long held that ordinances that are regulatory, but not prohibitory, do not conflict with state law.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Teefey
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 24 S.W.3d at 685-86;
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  Page Western, Inc. v. Community Fire Prot. Dist.
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 636 S.W.2d 65, 67 (Mo. banc 1982); 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 State ex rel. Hewlett v. Womach
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 196 S.W.2d 809, 814 (Mo. banc 1946).
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Sunshine responds that Ordinance 2074 is a complete prohibition, which conflicts with state law.  Cities may not enact ordinances that conflict with state statutes or regulations.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Teefey
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 24 S.W.3d
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 at 685; 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Page Western,
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0  636 S.W.2d at 67; 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 State ex rel. Burnau v. Valley Park Fire Prot. Dist.
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 477 S.W.2d 734, 735-36 (Mo. App. 1972).  An ordinance conflicts with state law if it permits something state law prohibits, or prohibits something state law permits.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Teefey
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 24 S.W.3d
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 at 685.
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0   
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Whether the ordinance conflicts with state law is a question of law, which the Court reviews de novo.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Id. 
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 at 684.  
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 \tab State law authorizes under-$500 lenders.  
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Section 408.500 RSMo 2000
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 ; 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 Barry Serv. Agency Co. v. Manning
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 891 S.W.2d 882, 891 (Mo. App. 1995).  Sunshine thus operates a permitted business within the state of Missouri.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 \tab Under Ordinance 2074, short-term lending is "prohibited in all zoning districts of the City of St. Ann."  Where the city prohibits a business that state law permits, the city has the burden to show that the ordinance does not conflict with state law.  See
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  Nickols v. North Kansas City
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 214 S.W.2d 710, 712-13 (Mo. 1948); see also
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0  McKay Buick, Inc. v. Love
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 569 S.W.2d 740, 743 (Mo. banc 1978).  The city meets this burden by showing that its regulation is a valid exercise of the zoning power, that the state-authorized business is not an appropriate use within the city.  See, e.g., 
\plain \i \f1 \fs20 \cf0 McDermott v. Village of Calverton Park
\plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 , 454 S.W.2d 577, 581-84 (Mo. banc 1970).  In this case, the city has not shown that Ordinance 2074 is a valid exercise of the zoning power.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qc \li0 \fi0 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \b \f1 \fs20 \cf0 IV.
\par \pard \ltrpar\qj \li0 \fi720 \ri0 \sl480 \sb0 \sa0 \plain \f1 \fs20 \cf0 The judgment of the circuit court is reversed, and the case remanded.
